  <main>

    <!-- SECTION 1: The question most procurement engineers don't ask early enough -->
    <section class="oneL-reality">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-reality-grid">
          <div class="oneL-reality-text">
            <p class="oneL-eyebrow">Procurement engineering perspective</p>
            <h1>1 Layer PCB: Is a single-sided board the right structure for your product?</h1>
            <p class="oneL-lead">
              Every procurement engineer evaluating a 1-layer PCB faces the same starting question: <em>will a board with copper on one side deliver the electrical performance, mechanical reliability, and assembly yield my production line needs?</em>
            </p>
            <p>
              The answer is not a simple yes or no. A single-sided PCB is the lowest-cost substrate structure available, but it carries real trade-offs in routing density, signal integrity, component placement flexibility, and mechanical rigidity. The engineering decision depends on trace count, component count, operating environment, assembly method, and volume.
            </p>
            <p>
              This page exists to help you answer that question with data — not marketing. XFPCB manufactures 1-layer PCBs for LED lighting, power adapters, appliance controls, sensor modules, and cost-optimised consumer electronics. We also help buyers identify when a double-sided or multilayer board would be the more reliable long-term choice.
            </p>
            <div class="oneL-meta-badges">
              <span class="oneL-badge">FR-4 / CEM-1 / CEM-3 compatible</span>
              <span class="oneL-badge">Aluminum base option available</span>
              <span class="oneL-badge">HASL / Lead-free / OSP / ENIG</span>
              <span class="oneL-badge">Panel-optimised pricing</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="oneL-reality-visual">
            <div class="oneL-image-card">
              <img src="/images/675x542pcb.jpg" alt="XFPCB 1 layer single sided PCB board for export buyers" loading="eager">
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-callout">
              <strong>Engineering-first procurement:</strong> XFPCB provides CAM review, material recommendations, panel layout advice, and surface finish guidance before you commit to production. Every quote includes a DFM report.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 2: Decision framework — Single-sided vs Double-sided -->
    <section class="oneL-decision">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-section-label">
          <span class="oneL-label-tag">Decision framework</span>
          <h2>Single-sided vs double-sided: when does 1 layer make engineering sense?</h2>
          <p>The most valuable decision a procurement team makes is not which supplier to choose — it is whether the board structure itself fits the product. This comparison table maps the trade-offs with specific numbers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-compare-table-wrapper">
          <table class="oneL-compare-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Evaluation criterion</th>
                <th>1-Layer (single-sided) PCB</th>
                <th>2-Layer (double-sided) PCB</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Relative substrate cost</td>
                <td class="oneL-good">Baseline — lowest cost per cm²</td>
                <td class="oneL-neutral">+40–60% over 1-layer</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Routing density limit</td>
                <td>~1.0–1.5 traces/mm per side — one routing layer only</td>
                <td>~2.0–3.0 traces/mm total across both sides with PTH jumpers</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Component placement density</td>
                <td>Components on one side only. Wire jumpers or zero-ohm resistors needed for cross-traces.</td>
                <td>Components on both sides. PTH vias replace wire jumpers.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Typical assembly method</td>
                <td>Wave soldering, selective soldering, or manual — single pass</td>
                <td>Wave soldering or reflow — single or double pass</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Signal integrity ceiling</td>
                <td>&lt;10 MHz — no ground plane, higher loop inductance</td>
                <td>&lt;50 MHz — ground plane possible on bottom side</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Mechanical rigidity</td>
                <td>Lower — no copper on bottom reduces overall board stiffness by ~30% compared to equal-thickness double-sided board</td>
                <td>Higher — copper on both sides adds structural stiffness</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Best-fit applications</td>
                <td>LED tubes, power adapters, appliance relays, basic sensors, calculator-level circuits</td>
                <td>IoT nodes, motor drives, power supplies with feedback, display interfaces</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="oneL-criterion">Volume sweet spot</td>
                <td>1,000–100,000+ pcs — tooling amortises well at scale</td>
                <td>500–50,000 pcs — PTH adds per-board cost but avoids jumper labour</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-insight-box">
          <h4>Engineering insight</h4>
          <p>The crossover point where a 2-layer board becomes cheaper than a 1-layer board with jumpers is typically around <strong>8–12 jumper wires per board</strong> in medium-to-high volume. Before that threshold, the single-sided board with selective jumpers is usually the lower total-cost option. XFPCB can review your BOM and netlist to advise on the crossover before you finalise the layer count.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 3: Material selection guidance with specific numbers -->
    <section class="oneL-materials">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-section-label">
          <span class="oneL-label-tag">Material selection</span>
          <h2>Laminate materials for 1-layer PCBs: engineering properties and cost trade-offs</h2>
          <p>The laminate you choose determines electrical performance, thermal behaviour, mechanical stability, and unit cost. Most competitor pages list material names without the numbers that procurement engineers actually need to make a decision.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-mat-grid">
          <article class="oneL-mat-card">
            <div class="oneL-mat-header">
              <h3>FR-4</h3>
              <span class="oneL-mat-cost">Cost index: 1.0 (baseline)</span>
            </div>
            <ul class="oneL-mat-props">
              <li><strong>Tg:</strong> 130–140°C (standard) / 170–180°C (high-Tg)</li>
              <li><strong>Td (decomposition):</strong> 300–350°C</li>
              <li><strong>DK (1 MHz):</strong> 4.5–4.8</li>
              <li><strong>CTI:</strong> 175–250 V (class IIIa–IIIb)</li>
              <li><strong>Moisture absorption:</strong> 0.10–0.25%</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Best for general-purpose electronics, appliances, power adapters, and any board requiring UL recognition. FR-4 provides the best balance of mechanical strength, electrical insulation, and processability for 1-layer PCBs. Standard Tg is sufficient for most single-sided designs; high-Tg only needed for lead-free soldering with multiple thermal cycles.</p>
            <p class="oneL-mat-rec"><strong>Recommend when:</strong> Solderability, mechanical stability, and UL certification matter. Avoid when strict cost targets below $0.02/cm² justify a CEM grade.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-mat-card">
            <div class="oneL-mat-header">
              <h3>CEM-1</h3>
              <span class="oneL-mat-cost">Cost index: 0.70–0.80</span>
            </div>
            <ul class="oneL-mat-props">
              <li><strong>Tg:</strong> 120–130°C</li>
              <li><strong>Construction:</strong> Woven glass fabric top + cellulose paper core</li>
              <li><strong>DK (1 MHz):</strong> 4.8–5.2</li>
              <li><strong>CTI:</strong> 175 V (class IIIa)</li>
              <li><strong>Punchability:</strong> Excellent — suitable for high-speed punching instead of routing</li>
            </ul>
            <p>CEM-1 uses a paper core with glass fabric top and bottom layers. It punches cleanly at high speed, making it attractive for very high-volume 1-layer PCB production where the tooling cost can be amortised. The trade-off is lower mechanical strength and higher moisture sensitivity compared to FR-4.</p>
            <p class="oneL-mat-rec"><strong>Recommend when:</strong> High volume (50,000+ pcs/year), non-critical consumer electronics, cost is the primary driver, and the board does not experience high humidity or thermal cycling.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-mat-card">
            <div class="oneL-mat-header">
              <h3>CEM-3</h3>
              <span class="oneL-mat-cost">Cost index: 0.75–0.85</span>
            </div>
            <ul class="oneL-mat-props">
              <li><strong>Tg:</strong> 125–135°C</li>
              <li><strong>Construction:</strong> Glass fabric throughout (unlike CEM-1)</li>
              <li><strong>DK (1 MHz):</strong> 4.7–5.1</li>
              <li><strong>CTI:</strong> 175 V (class IIIa)</li>
              <li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Opaque white or natural — transparent if backlit</li>
            </ul>
            <p>CEM-3 is sometimes described as a "punchable FR-4 alternative." Unlike CEM-1, it uses glass fabric reinforcement throughout the laminate, giving it closer mechanical properties to FR-4 while still supporting high-speed punching for through-holes and outlines. It is commonly used in consumer electronics where cost pressure is high but some through-hole reliability is still expected.</p>
            <p class="oneL-mat-rec"><strong>Recommend when:</strong> Volume is moderate-to-high, material cost is critical, but you need better hole-wall quality than CEM-1 provides.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-mat-card">
            <div class="oneL-mat-header">
              <h3>Aluminum base (IMS)</h3>
              <span class="oneL-mat-cost">Cost index: 1.5–3.0 (depending on dielectric thickness)</span>
            </div>
            <ul class="oneL-mat-props">
              <li><strong>Thermal conductivity:</strong> 1.0–4.0 W/m·K (dielectric layer) / 150–220 W/m·K (aluminum base)</li>
              <li><strong>Dielectric breakdown:</strong> 3–6 kV (depending on dielectric thickness)</li>
              <li><strong>Typical dielectric thickness:</strong> 50–150 µm</li>
              <li><strong>Copper weight:</strong> 1 oz to 6 oz available</li>
              <li><strong>Board thickness:</strong> 0.8–3.2 mm (base + dielectric + copper)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Aluminum-base PCBs (Insulated Metal Substrate) replace the FR-4 core with an aluminum plate covered by a thermally conductive dielectric layer and copper foil. The metal base acts as a heat spreader, pulling heat away from LEDs, power transistors, and rectifiers. The dielectric layer is the performance bottleneck — thinner dielectric = better thermal transfer but lower voltage isolation.</p>
            <p class="oneL-mat-rec"><strong>Recommend when:</strong> LED lighting (≥0.5 W per LED), power converters with heat-generating components, automotive lighting, or any board where junction temperature must stay below 85°C in a sealed enclosure.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 4: Surface finish decision matrix -->
    <section class="oneL-finish">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-section-label">
          <span class="oneL-label-tag">Surface finish selection</span>
          <h2>Choosing the right surface finish for a 1-layer PCB: price, shelf life, and solderability</h2>
          <p>The surface finish accounts for roughly 5–15% of the total board cost, but it can determine whether your assembly line runs at 98% yield or 92% yield. For single-sided PCBs, the finish choice is usually between HASL, lead-free HASL, OSP, and (less commonly) ENIG. Here is the decision matrix.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-finish-grid">
          <div class="oneL-finish-card oneL-finish-highlight">
            <div class="oneL-finish-top">
              <h3>HASL (Hot Air Solder Leveling)</h3>
              <div class="oneL-finish-cost">Lowest cost</div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-finish-body">
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Cost impact</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Baseline (1.0×)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Shelf life</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">12 months (controlled environment)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Pad flatness</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Moderate — uneven surface tolerable for wave solder</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Solderability</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Excellent — best for wave and selective soldering</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Best for</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">THT and wave-soldered assemblies. Most common choice for 1-layer boards.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="oneL-finish-card">
            <div class="oneL-finish-top">
              <h3>Lead-free HASL</h3>
              <div class="oneL-finish-cost">Low cost (RoHS)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-finish-body">
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Cost impact</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">1.1–1.15× vs HASL</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Shelf life</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">12 months</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Pad flatness</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Moderate — similar to leaded HASL</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Solderability</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Good — requires higher soldering temperature (~260°C peak)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Best for</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">RoHS-compliant products. Standard choice for EU-bound electronics.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="oneL-finish-card">
            <div class="oneL-finish-top">
              <h3>OSP (Organic Solderability Preservative)</h3>
              <div class="oneL-finish-cost">Low cost, short shelf life</div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-finish-body">
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Cost impact</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">0.85–0.95× vs HASL</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Shelf life</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">6 months — shorter if high humidity</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Pad flatness</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Excellent — perfectly flat surface</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Solderability</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Good — requires clean handling and timely assembly</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Best for</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">SMT with fine-pitch parts. Boards assembled within weeks of delivery.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="oneL-finish-card">
            <div class="oneL-finish-top">
              <h3>ENIG (Electroless Nickel Immersion Gold)</h3>
              <div class="oneL-finish-cost">Moderate cost</div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-finish-body">
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Cost impact</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">1.5–2.0× vs HASL</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Shelf life</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">12+ months — very stable</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Pad flatness</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Excellent — flat, coplanar surface for fine-pitch assembly</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Solderability</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Excellent — consistent wetting, good for multiple reflow cycles</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-finish-metric">
                <span class="oneL-fm-label">Best for</span>
                <span class="oneL-fm-value">Aluminum PCBs, fine-pitch SMT, long storage before assembly, or repeated thermal exposure.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-insight-box">
          <h4>Practical recommendation for 1-layer PCBs</h4>
          <p>For the majority of single-sided boards going through wave soldering, <strong>standard HASL</strong> is the most cost-effective and solder-reliable finish. Upgrade to <strong>lead-free HASL</strong> only if RoHS compliance is required. Switch to <strong>OSP</strong> if you need flat pads for SMT components and you can schedule assembly within 4–6 weeks of receiving boards. Use <strong>ENIG</strong> on aluminum-base PCBs or when the board will be stored before assembly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 5: Panel utilization economics -->
    <section class="oneL-panel">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-section-label">
          <span class="oneL-label-tag">Manufacturing economics</span>
          <h2>Panel utilisation: the hidden cost lever in 1-layer PCB pricing</h2>
          <p>Most buyers compare quotes by board-area price. The real driver of unit cost is how efficiently your board fits onto a standard production panel. For 1-layer PCBs, panel utilisation directly determines material waste, process time, and the number of boards per press cycle.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-panel-content">
          <div class="oneL-panel-text">
            <h3>Standard panel sizes and their economics</h3>
            <p>XFPCB typically builds 1-layer PCBs on standard laminate panel sizes. The most common are:</p>
            <ul class="oneL-panel-list">
              <li><strong>940 mm × 620 mm</strong> (37 × 24.4 in) — Largest standard, best for high-volume panelisation, but requires larger tooling</li>
              <li><strong>610 mm × 510 mm</strong> (24 × 20 in) — Common production panel, good balance of utilisation and handling</li>
              <li><strong>500 mm × 400 mm</strong> (19.7 × 15.7 in) — Typical for mid-volume, easier to handle in plating and solder mask lines</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How panelisation affects cost per board</h3>
            <p>The number of boards per panel is rarely a whole-number fit. The two key calculations are:</p>
            <ul class="oneL-panel-list">
              <li><strong>Panel utilisation ratio</strong> = (total board area on panel) ÷ (panel area). Target: ≥75%. Below 60%, material waste starts dominating cost.</li>
              <li><strong>Tooling cost amortisation:</strong> The initial tooling (punch die or routing program) is a fixed cost. At 500 boards, tooling may add $0.08–0.15 per board. At 50,000 boards, it drops below $0.005 per board.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Outline method: routing vs. V-scoring vs. punching</h3>
            <p>The outline method significantly affects per-board cost at different volumes:</p>
            <ul class="oneL-panel-list">
              <li><strong>CNC routing</strong> — Flexible, no tooling charge. Best for prototypes and low-volume (&lt;1,000 pcs). Adds $0.02–0.08 per board routing time.</li>
              <li><strong>V-scoring</strong> — Low per-board cost, clean break. Requires straight edges. Ideal for rectangular boards in mid-to-high volume.</li>
              <li><strong>Punching (steel rule die)</strong> — Highest upfront tooling cost ($200–800 per die), but lowest per-board cost at high volume (&gt;10,000 pcs). 1–3 seconds per board versus 30–60 seconds per board for routing. Only suitable for CEM-1, CEM-3, or thin FR-4.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="oneL-panel-numbers">
            <div class="oneL-stat-block">
              <span class="oneL-stat-value">75%</span>
              <span class="oneL-stat-label">Minimum panel utilisation target</span>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-stat-block">
              <span class="oneL-stat-value">$0.005</span>
              <span class="oneL-stat-label">Per-board tooling cost at 50,000 pcs</span>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-stat-block">
              <span class="oneL-stat-value">3 s</span>
              <span class="oneL-stat-label">Punch time per board vs. 45 s routing</span>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-stat-block">
              <span class="oneL-stat-value">1.5–5.0×</span>
              <span class="oneL-stat-label">Cost per cm² range (FR-4 vs punched CEM-1 at volume)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION 6: Cost driver breakdown -->
    <section class="oneL-costs">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-section-label">
          <span class="oneL-label-tag">Cost transparency</span>
          <h2>What actually drives the price of a 1-layer PCB</h2>
          <p>Rather than a black-box quote, here is how each specification choice moves the unit price. Understanding these drivers helps procurement engineers target the most impactful cost-reduction levers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-cost-drivers">
          <div class="oneL-driver-row">
            <div class="oneL-driver-name">
              <span class="oneL-driver-icon">①</span>
              <div>
                <h4>Material grade</h4>
                <p>FR-4 vs CEM-1 vs CEM-3 vs aluminum</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-driver-bar-wrapper">
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 100%;">FR-4: baseline</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-secondary">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 78%;">CEM-3: −22%</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-secondary">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 73%;">CEM-1: −27%</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-costly">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 180%;">Aluminum: +50–200%</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="oneL-driver-row">
            <div class="oneL-driver-name">
              <span class="oneL-driver-icon">②</span>
              <div>
                <h4>Copper weight</h4>
                <p>Impact on material and etching cost</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-driver-bar-wrapper">
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 100%;">1 oz: baseline</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-costly">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 135%;">2 oz: +30–40%</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-costly">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 175%;">3 oz: +60–90%</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="oneL-driver-row">
            <div class="oneL-driver-name">
              <span class="oneL-driver-icon">③</span>
              <div>
                <h4>Surface finish</h4>
                <p>HASL vs lead-free vs OSP vs ENIG</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="oneL-driver-bar-wrapper">
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 100%;">HASL: baseline</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-secondary">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 113%;">Lead-free: +10–15%</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-secondary">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 93%;">OSP: −5–10%</span>
              </div>
              <div class="oneL-driver-bar oneL-bar-costly">
                <span class="oneL-driver-fill" style="width: 160%;">ENIG: +50–100%</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="oneL-driver-row">
            <div class="oneL-driver-name">
