    <!-- SECTION 7: When NOT to use 1-layer PCB -->
    <section class="oneL-notfor">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="oneL-section-label">
          <span class="oneL-label-tag">Engineering honesty</span>
          <h2>When a 1-layer PCB is the wrong choice</h2>
          <p>Every PCB structure has limits. These are the conditions where a single-sided board will create more problems than it solves — and where XFPCB will recommend a double-sided or multilayer board instead.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-notfor-grid">
          <article class="oneL-notfor-card oneL-notfor-severe">
            <h3>Signal edges faster than 10 MHz</h3>
            <p>Without a ground plane, the return current path for high-frequency signals is uncontrolled. Loop inductance increases, and the board will radiate EMI. At 50 MHz and above, the signal integrity degradation can render the circuit non-functional. A 2-layer board with a ground plane is the minimum viable structure for clocked digital circuits.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-notfor-card">
            <h3>More than 15–20 components</h3>
            <p>As component count increases, the trace routing on a single layer becomes circuitous. Wire jumpers or zero-ohm resistors accumulate. Each jumper adds a reliability point, a manual assembly step, and a potential failure mode. Beyond 15–20 components, the total-cost crossover with a 2-layer board has usually been reached.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-notfor-card">
            <h3>Board size above 200 cm² (31 sq in)</h3>
            <p>Large single-sided boards lack the structural stiffness of double-sided boards at the same thickness. Copper on only one side means the board will bow or twist more under thermal stress during soldering. For boards over 200 cm², XFPCB recommends either moving to a double-sided structure or increasing board thickness to 1.6 mm minimum and specifying flatness requirements.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-notfor-card">
            <h3>Fine-pitch SMT components (≤0.5 mm pitch)</h3>
            <p>Single-sided PCBs with HASL finish have uneven pad surfaces. This can cause tombstoning, solder balling, or poor wetting on fine-pitch parts. If your design includes QFP or SOP packages with 0.5 mm or tighter pitch, XFPCB will recommend OSP or ENIG finish — and if density is also an issue, a 2-layer board.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-notfor-card">
            <h3>Vibration or high-G environments</h3>
            <p>A single-sided PCB in a vibrating environment (automotive, industrial machinery, power tools) is at higher risk of copper trace fatigue and solder joint failure because the thermal and mechanical stresses are concentrated on a single copper layer. Through-hole components on a double-sided board provide stronger mechanical anchorage.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="oneL-notfor-card">
            <h3>High ambient humidity or condensation exposure</h3>
            <p>In humid environments, single-sided boards with exposed traces on the component side can experience surface leakage current, electrochemical migration (dendrite growth), or corrosion — especially if the solder mask coverage is incomplete at trace edges. Conformal coating can mitigate this, but a double-sided board with ground plane shielding may be a more robust solution.</p>
          </article>
        </div>

        <div class="oneL-verdict-box">
          <p><strong>XFPCB policy:</strong> If our CAM review identifies any of these risk conditions in your design, we will flag them before quoting. We would rather help you select the right board structure than manufacture a board that creates problems at assembly or in the field.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

